  "prompt": "How much sugar is good for health?",
  "response": "The amount of sugar considered \"good\" for health depends on various factors, including age, sex, activity level, and overall dietary habits. However, health organizations provide general guidelines to help limit added sugar intake for better health:\n\n### General Recommendations:\n1. **World Health Organization (WHO):**\n   - Recommends limiting **added sugars** to **less than 10% of total daily calorie intake**.\n   - Suggests a further reduction to **less than 5%** (about 25 grams or 6 teaspoons per day) for additional health benefits.\n\n2. **American Heart Association (AHA):**\n   - Men: No more than **9 teaspoons (36 grams)** of added sugar per day.\n   - Women: No more than **6 teaspoons (25 grams)** of added sugar per day.\n\n3. **Dietary Guidelines for Americans:**\n   - Recommends limiting added sugars to **less than 10% of daily calories**. For a 2,000-calorie diet, this is about **50 grams (12 teaspoons)**.\n\n### Natural vs. Added Sugars:\n- **Natural sugars** (found in fruits, vegetables, and dairy) are generally healthier because they come with nutrients like fiber, vitamins, and minerals.\n- **Added sugars** (found in processed foods, sodas, and sweets) should be limited, as they contribute to empty calories and health risks.\n\n### Health Risks of Excessive Sugar:\n- Weight gain and obesity\n- Increased risk of type 2 diabetes\n- Heart disease\n- Dental cavities\n- Fatty liver disease\n\n### Tips to Reduce Sugar Intake:\n- Read food labels to identify added sugars.\n- Choose whole, unprocessed foods over packaged snacks.\n- Limit sugary beverages like soda and juice.\n- Use natural sweeteners (e.g., fruit) in moderation.\n\nIf you have specific health conditions or dietary needs, consult a healthcare professional or registered dietitian for personalized advice.",
